eligious freedom, and state power, yet it has had different salience, and been understood differently, from place to place and time to time. The volume brings together essays from an international array of experts in law and religion, in order to examine the public/private distinction in comparative perspective. The essays focus on the cultures and religions of the ancient Mediterranean, in the formative periods of Greece and Rome and the religions of Judaism, Christianity and Islam. Particular attention is given to the private exercise of religion, the relation between public norms and private life, and the division between public and private space and the place of religion therein.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLaw, GreekvHistory. 0aLaw, GreekxHistory. 0aPrivacy, Right of (Jewish law)vHistory. 0aPrivacy, Right of (Jewish law)xHistory. 0aPrivacy, Right ofvHistory. 0aPrivacy, Right ofxHistory. 0aPublic law (Greek law)vHistory. 0aPublic law (Greek law)xHistory. 0aPublic law (Roman law)vHistory. 0aPublic law (Roman law)xHistory. 0aReligion and lawvHistory. 0aReligion and lawxHistory. 0aRoman lawxHistory. 4aAntike Religion. 4aAntikes Christentum. 4aFamilie. 4aRechtsgeschichte. 4aÖffentlichkeit. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aAncient Christianity.  aAncient Judaism.  aIslam.  aprivate.  apublic.1 aAndo, Clifford, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBegemann, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDohrmann, Natalie B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEidinow, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Shamsy, Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans Grubbs, Jud